03781nam a22006255i 9780292761735DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211995txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927617357 a10.7560/7706762doi  a(DE-B1597)587659  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF2679.2.C5b.R443 1995 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a338.109892131 aReed, Richard K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProphets of Agroforestry :bGuaraní Communities and Commercial Gathering /cRichard K. Reed. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1995  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Yerba, Society, and the State in Mbaracayú -- t3. Kinship, Households, and Community -- t4. Leadership and Religion -- t5. Chiripa Agroforestry -- t6. Patrones, Capataces, and Caciques -- t7. Conclusions -- tPostscript: The Chiripá and Recent Changes -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor almost four centuries, the indigenous Chiripá (Guaraní) people of eastern Paraguay have maintained themselves as a distinct society and culture, despite continual and often intense relations with Paraguayan society and the international economy. In this study, Richard K. Reed explores the economic and social basis for this ethnic autonomy. Reed finds that Chiripá economic power derives from their practice of commercial agroforestry. Unlike Latin American indigenous societies that have been forced to clear land for commercial agriculture, the Chiripá continue to harvest and sell forest products, such as caffeinated yerba mate, without destroying the forests. Reed also explores the relation of this complex economy to Chiripá social organization and shows how flexible kin ties allowed the Chiripá to adapt to the pressure and opportunities of the commercial economy without adopting the authoritarian nature of rural Paraguayan society. These findings offer important insights into the relations among indigenous groups, nation-states, and the international economy. They also provide a timely alternative model for sustainable management of subtropical forests that will be of interest in the fields of development and environmental studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aChiripá IndiansxAgriculture. 0aChiripá IndiansxEconomic conditions. 0aChiripá IndiansxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292761735423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292761735/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK